</li><li class="sense" hclass="sense" id="aesthetic_sng_5" sensenum="2" htag="li"><span class="sensetop" htag="span" hclass="sensetop"><div class="variants" hclass="variants" htag="div" type="alt"><span class="v-g"><span class="v">aesthetics</span></span></div></span> <span class="grammar" hclass="grammar" htag="span">[uncountable]</span> <span class="def" htag="span" hclass="def">the branch of philosophy that studies the principles of beauty, especially in art</span>      </li><div class="collapse" hclass="collapse" htag="div"><span class="unbox" id="aesthetic3_unbox_1" unbox="wordorigin" dup="fky"><span class="box_title">Word Origin</span><span class="body"><span class="p">late 18th cent. (in the sense ‘relating to perception by the senses’): from Greek <span class="ei">aisthētikos</span>, from <span class="ei">aisthēta</span> ‘perceptible things’, from <span class="ei">aisthesthai</span> ‘perceive’. The sense ‘concerned with beauty’ was first used in German in the mid 18th cent. and adopted into English in the early 19th cent., but its use was controversial until much later in the century.</span></span></span></div></ol><span class="dictlink-g"><span class="dictlink">See <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/american_english/aesthetic_2" title=" definition in American English
